What is estrogen?

Estrogens in the human body are mainly produced by the ovaries and placenta. Natural estrogens include estradiol, estrone, and estriol, with estrone being the most active estrogen in the body.

The estrogen secreted by our bodies is professionally called "endogenous estrogen"; estrogen derived from artificial synthesis or food is called "exogenous estrogen".

The Proceedings of the Royal Society B points out that the source of female charm is estrogen, which can make women's skin delicate and shapely.

First, it stimulates the development of female secondary sexual characteristics . There is an old Chinese saying that "a girl changes a lot at eighteen," largely due to the secretion of estrogen.

Second, estrogen promotes the proliferation of the uterus and endometrium , and embryo implantation is inseparable from estrogen.

Third, it promotes bone growth and calcium deposition . Osteoporosis is common after menopause because estrogen secretion gradually decreases after menopause.

Fourth, estrogen also keeps our vaginal environment acidic , which improves our ability to resist bacterial infections and gynecological diseases. This is why the vaginal infection rate increases in women after estrogen levels drop during menopause.

Fifth, regulating the menstrual cycle : Estrogen and progesterone work together to form the menstrual cycle, and our regular menstrual cycle is closely related to estrogen.

Sixth, fat metabolism : Many women tend to accumulate fat in their lower abdomen as they reach middle age, which is largely related to the decrease in estrogen secretion.

7. It has effects on many organs throughout the body . Estrogen has certain effects on the health of the cardiovascular system and the vitality of the brain.

